<h2>
    Understanding Chum Salmon
</h2>
<h3>
    What Are Chum Salmon?
</h3>
<p>
    Chum salmon (<i>Oncorhynchus keta</i>), also known as dog salmon due to the male's prominent canine-like teeth during spawning, are one of the five Pacific salmon species. They are known for their vibrant coloration during spawning season—males often display bold vertical stripes in shades of purple, green, and red.
</p>
<p>
    Unlike Chinook or Coho salmon, chum are not commonly targeted for their table quality. However, they provide an exhilarating fight on the line and play an essential ecological role in Oregon’s river systems.
</p>
