</h2>
<h3>
    Licensing and Permits
</h3>
<p>
    To fish for salmon in Oregon, you'll need:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Oregon Angling License</strong>
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Combined Angling Tag</strong>
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Columbia River Basin Endorsement</strong> (for certain tributaries)
    </li>
</ul>
<p>
    Be aware that <strong>Washington State licenses are required</strong> if fishing on the north side of the Columbia or in WA rivers like the Lewis or Kalama.
</p>
<h3>
    Catch Limits and Restrictions
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Retention of chum salmon is often prohibited in Oregon.</strong>
    </li>
    <li>
        In Washington, some rivers <strong>allow limited retention</strong>—check WDFW guidelines.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Always consult current regulations</strong> on river-specific allowances before heading out.
    </li>
</ul>
