</h3>
<p>
    Both methods are effective, but your choice may depend on water conditions:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Fly Fishing</strong> – Effective in shallow runs. Use bright streamer flies resembling salmon eggs or shrimp.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Spin Fishing</strong> – Good for deeper pools. Use jigs, spinners, or drift rigs with yarn balls.
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    Effective Casting Strategies
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Drift Fishing</strong> – Cast upstream and allow your lure to drift naturally.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Float Fishing</strong> – Ideal in slow-moving water. Keeps bait in the strike zone longer.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Sight Fishing</strong> – Look for chum near gravel bars or tailouts where they gather to spawn.
    </li>
</ul>
